<F P=100> LATIN AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> COLOMBIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Guerrilla Attack Forces Shutdown of Pipeline </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Guerrilla Attack Forces Shutdown of Pipeline </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0804000294 Mexico City NOTIMEX in Spanish 2124 GMT 4 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> PA0804000294 </F>
<F P=104>  Mexico City NOTIMEX </F>
<F P=105>  Spanish </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Santa Fe de Bogota, 4 Apr (NOTIMEX) -- The Colombian 
enterprise ECOPETROL today stopped pumping crude oil through the 
Cano Limon-Covenas pipeline, the country's largest, after a new 
attack by the guerrillas. 
  ECOPETROL sources said the sabotage, which caused a moderate 
fire and spilled an unspecified quantity of crude oil, occurred 
at Km 150 between Arauquita and La Esmeralda, near the border 
with Venezuela. 
  According to the report, members of the National Liberation 
Army detonated three dynamite charges against the pipeline, 
damaging a sizable portion thereof and forcing suspension of the 
pumping, a suspension that will continue until it is repaired in 
a few days. 
  Colombia's oil infrastructure has become one of the Simon 
Bolivar Guerrilla Coordinating Board's main targets. The 
guerrilla organization attempts to thwart the participation of 
multinational enterprises in the export of oil. 
  Authorities of Arauca Department, where the recently 
discovered Cusiana oil fields are located, mounted a strong 
security operation to preclude new attacks. 

</TEXT>

