<ABS>  FOUO </ABS>
<DATE1>   13 April 1994 </DATE1>
<F P=100> LATIN AMERICA </F>
<F P=101> COLOMBIA </F>
<H3> <TI>   Roundup of Guerrilla Activities </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Roundup of Guerrilla Activities </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   PA0704223394 </F>
<F P=103> PA0704223394 </F>
<F P=104></F>



<TEXT>
BFN 

    [Editorial Report] The following is a compilation of 
reports on Colombian guerrilla activities monitored through 4 
April. 
  Two police officers were killed when a two-kg explosive 
device launched against the home of Fabio Ospina Giraldo, former 
secretary of the Administrative Services of the Valle 
Governorship, exploded in southern Cali. This is the second 
time that police officers assigned to protect Ospina have been 
killed. (Santa Fe de Bogota EL TIEMPO in Spanish 30 March 94 p 
8a) 
  The Revolutionary Armed Forces of Colombia's (FARC) 12th 
Front burned 27 new vehicles being transported by car carriers 
on the Barrancabermeja-Puerto Araujo highway. Subversive 
checkpoints have appeared throughout the department. Military 
units in armored vehicles initiated an intense sweep operation 
where daily the guerrillas' actions cause significant losses to 
the transportation sector. (Santa Fe de Bogota Inravision 
Television Cadena 1 in Spanish 1800 GMT 31 March 94) 
  Army troops supported by helicopters attempted yesterday to 
encounter two guerrilla commandos that last Friday attacked two 
military patrols in Boyaca and Cesar, leaving eight dead 
soldiers and 11 wounded. Meanwhile, on 26 March ELN (Army of 
National Liberation) rebels dynamited once more the Cano 
Limon-Covenas oil pipeline at the Km 60 marker in Arauquita 
Municipality. As a result pumping was halted although it was 
resumed yesterday. In Bogota, the XIII Brigade uncovered a 
secret factory of guerrilla uniforms. (Santa Fe de Bogota EL 
TIEMPO in Spanish 27 March 94 p 19a) 
  Pedro Jose Chavarria David, alias "Colacho" or "El Mono," 
third man of the dissolved Popular Liberation Army's (EPL) 
dissident movement, was captured together with two other persons 
in a Medellin neighborhood, official sources reported today. 
The sources said that Chavarria is in charge of the finances of 
the EPL's dissident movement, which is comprised of 150 men who 
operate in the Antioquia, Risaralda, and Caldas departments. 
(Madrid EFE in Spanish 1637 GMT 1 April 94) 
  The Colombian Government today blamed FARC for the murder of 
Prospero Merino, councilman and political leader of the 
Caribbean community in Cienaga, Magdalena Department, in an 
attempt to hamper the 29 May presidential elections. Merino was 
shot in a small town outside Cienaga by five men who also killed 
Luis Sanchez accompanying him while two others were wounded. 
(Hamburg DPA in Spanish 1535 GMT 3 April 94) 
  Army sources disclosed an alleged terrorist plan by the 
guerrilla against several government institutions at the Narino 
Department. Authorities confirmed that at the former Public 
Works Ministry's camp were seized 230 kg of dynamite, 1,250 
meters of slow fuse, as well as maps of institutions to be 
allegedly attacked by the Farc's 29th Front. (Santa Fe de 
Bogota Emisoras Caracol Network in Spanish 1200 GMT 4 April 94) 
  On 30 March, guerrillas set 27 new cars and the trailer in 
which they were being transported on the Pan-American Highway 
near Barrancabermeja. In addition, a bus -- which was carrying 
no passengers -- was also destroyed on the road between 
Bucaramanga and Maicao. It was also reported that during the 
past few hours army troops killed seven FARC and ELN guerrillas 
during clashes in Santander and Putumayo. (Santa Fe de Bogota EL 
TIEMPO in Spanish 2 April 94 pp 1A, 8A) 
  Two presumed FARC guerrillas were killed on 1 April during 
clashes in the rural area of Sampues, Sucre Department. The 
Army confiscated a .38-caliber revolver, a .9-mm pistol, 
ammunition, and subversive propaganda. (Santa Fe de Bogota EL 
TIEMPO in Spanish 3 April 94 p 16A) 

</TEXT>

