<H3> <TI>   FOCUS Says Two RAF Members Escaped at Bad Kleinen </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    FOCUS Says Two RAF Members Escaped at Bad Kleinen </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    BKA Denies FOCUS Report </H4>

<F P=102> AU0704112394 Hamburg DPA in German 0958 GMT 7 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU0704112394 </F>
<F P=104>  Hamburg DPA </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Excerpt] Wiesbaden (DPA) -- The Federal Office of 
Criminal Investigation (BKA) has rejected information in the new 
magazine FOCUS that four members of the Red Army Faction (RAF) 
might have escaped during the antiterrorist action of Bad 
Kleinen. These assumptions are wrong and do not correspond to 
the facts, BKA spokesman Hans-Georg Fuchs said in Wiesbaden on 
Thursday. However, the BKA does not wish to initiate any legal 
steps against FOCUS, it was stated. 
  It is true that on 24 June 1993, that is, three days before 
the action, the police filmed two persons who have so far not 
been identified and who were also at the expected meeting point 
of presumed RAF members Birgit Hogefeld and Wolfgang Grams. 
However, the investigators do not have any evidence that the 
man and the woman whom they filmed are terrorists, the BKA 
reported. 
  At the same time, the BKA rejected information from FOCUS 
that authorities are meanwhile proceeding on the assumption that 
the couple filmed might have participated in the murder of Trust 
Agency chief Detlef Karsten Rohwedder on 1 April 1991. A 
relevant "internal BKA paper" to which the magazine refers in 
its report is not known in the BKA, it was stated. 
  According to Fuchs, the magazine's assertion that the BKA 
investigators had filmed another couple who were only later 
recognized as presumed RAF members Daniela Klette and 
Ernst-Volker Staub at the Bad Kleinen station five hours before 
the antiterrorist action is equally wrong. The BKA does not 
have such a video recording, Fuchs said. [passage omitted] 

</TEXT>

