<H3> <TI>   No Details on Terrorist Expert's Death in Libya </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    No Details on Terrorist Expert's Death in Libya </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   AU1904101794 Munich FOCUS in German 18 Apr 94 p 13 </F>
<F P=103> AU1904101794 </F>
<F P=104>  Munich FOCUS </F>
<F P=105>  German </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "Mysterious Death in Libya"] </F>
  [Text] Being guessed at in the Federal Office for the 
Protection of the Constitution [BfV]: How did a high-ranking 
BfV official and his wife die in Libya? Silvian Becker, section 
head of BfV Department six (international terrorism), died in a 
military hospital in Tripoli the week before last. At the time 
of going to press, details of the circumstances, also regarding 
his wife's death, were still unknown to German officials; the 
bodies had not yet been released by Libya. 
  Becker had told the BfV in Cologne that he was going to 
Egypt 
for a vacation. A passenger car, which had obviously been used 
by the couple, was found undamaged in Tripoli. There is a basic 
ban on travel to Libya for all BfV employees. The BfV is 
wondering whether the tourists were kidnapped or enticed away 
from Egypt. Relatives claim that the Beckers went to Libya via 
Tunisia. The official was highly valued as an expert on the 
Middle East and northern Africa. His colleagues describe him as 
a "prudent man, and not an adventurous type." A double agent? 
"Very unlikely if you knew him," it is said in Cologne. 

