<H3> <TI>   UK Carrier Targetted by Terrorists </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    UK Carrier Targetted by Terrorists </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Attack Linked to Strikes Against Serbs </H4>

<F P=102> LD1104160994 London PRESS ASSOCIATION in English 1515 GMT 11 
Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1104160994 </F>
<F P=104>  London PRESS ASSOCIATION </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by Charles Miller, Defence Correspondent, PA News] </F>
  [Text] An abortive attempt by Greek terrorists to hit the 
carrier Ark Royal with anti-tank rockets could be linked to 
Britain's support for strikes against the Bosnian Serbs, it was 
disclosed today. 
  It is believed the ultranationalist November 17 guerilla 
group attempted to hit the 20,000-ton carrier with two 88 mm 
rockets as it was docked in the port of Piraeus near Athens. 
  Home-made rocket launchers with rockets and automatic timers 
were found in a field 200 yards from where the ship was docked, 
police said. 
  The search was launched after the guerilla group called a 
radio station to say it had tried to attack the ship, which left 
Piraeus early today after a week's maintenance. 
  Police said they thought the rockets aimed at the Ark Royal 
were set to go off last week but rain had fouled the timers, 
thwarting the attack. 
  The guerrillas also claimed responsibility for a rocket 
attack on a US insurance company and a time-bomb attack on a 
Dutch insurance company today. The blasts caused damage but no 
injuries. 
  Ark Royal and its sister ship Invincible have been 
alternating on six-month tours of duty since January last year 
in the Adriatic as part of Nato's operations to enforce the 
no-fly zone over Bosnia. 
  The operation has been directed primarily at Bosnian Serb 
and 
Serb aircraft and there has been concern in Greece about the 
Nato mission because of deep historical and religious links with 
the Serbs. 
  Ark Royal set sail from Piraeus completely unaware of the 
potentially disastrous failed attack, said Royal Navy officials. 
  A Whitehall source said: "This group of terrorists is 
ultranationalist and, as such, support the Serbs. The 
connection is not too difficult to make." 

</TEXT>

