<H3> <TI>   Commission Urges Tolerance To Solve Southeast Problem </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Commission Urges Tolerance To Solve Southeast Problem </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   TA1504150394 Ankara ANATOLIA in English 1425 GMT 15 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> TA1504150394 </F>
<F P=104>  Ankara ANATOLIA </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Ankara, April 15 (AA) -- A report prepared by a 
parliamentary commission in charge of detecting the existing 
problems and formulating measures on the southeast said that 
after the terrorism of the PKK [Workers Party of Kurdistan] is 
stopped, declaring a general amnesty is a must, to accomplish 
domestic peace. 
  The report also called for the restriction of the practice 
of 
regional governorates and the village guard systems. 
  The commission's chairman, Omur Lutfu Coskun, of the 
coalition member True Path Party (DYP), told a press conference 
today that, to prevent terror in the southeast, sensitivity is 
necessary so as not to regard all the region's people as 
potential criminals. 
  `The region should not be a place of exile for civil 
servants 
and the administrators should be loving and understanding in 
their relations with the region's people,' Coskun said. 
  Coskun cited other measures foreseen by their report as the 
formulation of urgent and lasting solutions to the problems of 
the region by local administrations, continuation of investments 
planned beforehand, encouragement of agriculture and animal 
breeding, opening new jobs. 
  The report stressed that practices based on using force 
would 
not facilitate the resolving of the problem and the tolerant 
attitude of the state would facilitate a solution sooner. 

</TEXT>

