<H3> <TI>   Al-Jama'ah al-Islamiyah Leader Killed </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Al-Jama'ah al-Islamiyah Leader Killed </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Further Report on Shooting </H4>

<F P=102> NC2504133694 Paris AFP in English 1314 GMT 25 Apr 94 </F>
<F P=103> NC2504133694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Cairo, April 25 (AFP) -- Police on Monday shot dead 
an Islamic militant leader and nine other fundamentalists during 
raids in Cairo and southern Egypt, an interior ministry 
spokesman said. 
  Tal'at Yasin Hammam, the head of the al-Jama'ah 
al-Islamiyah's armed wing, and five other militants were killed 
in a dawn clash with police at Hammam's apartment in northeast 
Cairo, the spokesman told AFP. 
  A military court in December 1992 sentenced Hammam, who has 
been wanted since 1989, and six others to death in their absence 
for belonging to a terrorist group bent on overthrowing Egypt's 
secular government. 
  All seven were reported to be veterans of the war in 
Afghanistan. 
  The raid came two weeks after the police chief heading the 
battle against the militants, General Ra'uf Khayrat, was 
murdered in Cairo. Al-Jama'ah al-Islamiyah said it carried out 
the attack. 
  In Asyut police killed four militants suspected of 
involvement in last Wednesday's killing of the head of security 
forces in the southern city, which is a militant stronghold. 
They were all students at Asyut University. 

</TEXT>

