<H3> <TI>   Detonators Stolen From Military, Possibly by Terrorists </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Detonators Stolen From Military, Possibly by Terrorists </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   NC2404144994 Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network in 
Greek 1130 GMT 24 Apr 94 </F>

<F P=103> NC2404144994 </F>
<F P=104>  Athens Elliniki Radhiofonia Radio Network </F>
<F P=105>  Greek </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text) Unidentified persons stole 7,000 detonators from 
the 28th Ammunition Warehouse, which is on Kos island. 
According to a statement issued by the Army General Staff 
[YES], the warehouse guard noticed last Thursday night that the 
door had been forced open. Following investigations it was 
established that 7,000 detonators were missing. The chief of 
YES instructed the ASDEN [Higher Military Command for the 
Interior and Islands] commander to visit the island. An 
extensive search is already in progress. 
  [Paris AFP in English at 1142 GMT on 24 April carries a 
related Athens-datelined report that adds that "investigators 
have not ruled out the possibility of a `terrorist' link, police 
said." 
  The AFP report continues: "Defense Mnister Yerasimos 
Arsenis, 
confirming local police reports of the theft Frriday night, said 
Sunday authorities were examining all hypotheses. 
  "Up to now he believed the thieves were `people who use 
dynamite for fishing,' or who wanted the detonators to make 
firecrackers for use during the Greek Orthodox Easter 
celebrations on May 1. 
  "However Greek police said they had not ruled out the 
possibility the detonators may have been stolen by people 
`planning a terrorist attack,' but added that this theory was 
`not favoured for the moment.'"] 

</TEXT>

